his is documented public behavior, so it seems like this wouldn't be a duplicate test after all.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering compile issues**\\n\\nIt seems that the issue with \\\"unable to resolve import\\\" suggests that the picocli library isn’t in the test compile classpath. I’m wondering if the Groovy compiler can load CliBuilder even without the picocli classes. It's possible that the Groovy runtime includes picocli, but the compile time doesn’t. I might need to avoid directly using picocli types. I should probably patch the code to remove the import and conduct testing to limit risks associated with this dependency issue.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_m6Pd4pvqCyyB1xSCXuUBDm1V|fc_06c9f43c6acf00b80169fff1e3d6b08190a37c328de520d624", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.apache.groovy/groovy-cli-picocli/4.0.24/src/test/groovy/org_apache_groovy/groovy_cli_picocli/Groovy_cli_picocliTest.groovy", "edits": [{"oldText": "import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.io.TempDir\nimport picocli.CommandLine.Model.OptionSpec\n\nimport java.io.File\nimport java.io.PrintWriter\nimport java.io.StringWriter\nimport java.net.URI", "newText": "import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.io.TempDir\n\nimport java.io.File\nimport java.io.PrintWriter\nimport java.io.StringWriter"}, {"oldText": "    @Test\n    void acceptsPicocliOptionSpecsAddedThroughLeftShift() {\n        CliBuilder cli = new CliBuilder(name: 'fetch')\n        TypedOption<URI> endpoint = cli << OptionSpec.builder('--endpoint')\n                .type(URI)\n                .paramLabel('<uri>')\n                .description('service endpoint')\n                .required(true)\n                .build()\n\n        OptionAccessor options = cli.parse([\n                '--endpoint', 'https://example.test/api',\n                'payload.json'\n        ] as String[])\n\n        assertThat(options).isNotNull()\n        assertThat(op